text: Help your father. The boar is very dangerous and you are a weak young man, but you must do something to help before it's too late.
Go for help from the other hunters. They have nets and spears, but running after them will take precious time.
Go hunting in the Bonewoods, a known home to wolves. Wolves are easier to find, but often roam in packs.
Go hunting near the mountains, where snow leopards occasionally roam. Snow leopards are hider to find, but are more often solitary and easier to take on one on one.
Go above the tree line. It will be easier to find a leopard, but much colder and you'll have less protection from the elements.
Stay near the tree line. It will be harder to find a leopard, but not as cold and you'll have the shelter of the trees.
Keep moving to a higher altitude. If you want to prove yourself as a man of the tribe, now is not the time to back down.
Return below the tree line. You aren't prepared for this cold and you can't prove yourself as a man by dying on the mountainside.
Light a torch and enter the cave. Leopards are notoriously elusive and if you've had the good fortune to find one, you must act, regardless of the consequences.
Wait outside for it to come out. Going into the cave alone would be suicide, and it's more prudent to wait to catch it by surprise.
Kill the leopard mother. In order to marry and have children of your own, you must complete the test, and the leopard must pay the price for your manhood.
Have mercy on the mother and her cubs. You will not be seen as a man by your tribe and you will suffer, but you do not want the mother's blood on your hands.
Set up camp and try again in the morning.
Attempt to bait a leopard with some food and lie in wait. However, you could end up luring some other animals instead.
Keep going. You're not going home a failure.
Return home. Your tribe will lose respect for you, but at least you will still be alive.
Take shelter amongst the rocky outcroppings and wait out the storm. You can resume the hunt later.
Attempt to return home. It will be dangerous trying to return home now, but it's better to risk it than get stranded in the blizzard or suffer an avalanche... or worse.
Shoot it now. You don't have a good look at the creature, but you may not get another chance.
Sneak up on it and throw your hatchet at it. It will give you a better shot and your hatchet will be more lethal, but getting closer will be dangerous. Snow leopards are lethal at close range.
Set up camp and start again in the morning. Hunting in the dark is too dangerous.
Light a torch and keep going. You could lure the wolves to you with the light in the dark.
Keep going into the southern wastes. The lands are dangerous, ruled by the Witch Lords, who are known for their cruelty to trespassers, but you might still find some wolves there.
Return home empty-handed. Your tribe will be disappointed in you and none of the girls will want to marry you, but at least you'll still be alive.
Try to talk your way out.
Run.
You notice one of the men carrying several freshly skinned wolf pelts. You offer to trade your dog for one.
Assault them head on. It's a higher risk maneuver, but making a head assault gives you a better chance for a kill. It also gives a better chance for the wolves to kill you.
Shoot them from afar. It's a lower risk attack, but the light is poor this late in the day and you may not get a good shot off before they run.
Throw some food to distract them, drop your torch, retreat, and shoot them from afar.
Drop your torch and run. The odds are decidedly not in your favor.
Charge them. Roar as if you were a large predator with your torch in hand and hack them apart with your hatchet.
Head into the ravine. The wolves might not stay long and if you wait, you might lose them.
Wait at the top of the ravine so you can keep watch. Going into the ravine could leave you easily surrounded should the wolves notice you first.
Take cover behind some trees and start shooting them with your bow.
There are too many of them. It's better to wait until a few leave.
Aim your bow and start shooting at them from afar. It's a longer distance and you may not get a good shot off.
Get closer, and then fire. You will get a better shot if engage at a closer range, but you risk the wolves attacking you if you get too close.

Choose Jeneth - With golden blond hair, a voluptuous body, and bronze skin, she is decidedly the most beautiful girl of the tribe. She has an affectionate and loving personality and shows great loyalty, but she is also known to be needy, petty, frail, and easily upset.

Choose Syla - A porcelain, raven haired girl, she is thin and lanky, and highly prized for her practical skills including spearfishing and archery. She is strong and protective. However, she is known to be harsh and demanding as well, and her fierce independence makes her opportunistic and undependable.

Demand both. Your brother is already married and you have proven yourself to be one of the strongest men of the tribe. You don't want to disappoint either of the girls and you will be a good husband to both.
Join the hunters and aid in procuring food for the migration.
Spend time with the elders learning more about management of the tribe.
Comfort her and ask her how she's feeling.
Hunt some fresh meat for her to help give her some energy.
Scold her and tell her to improve her attitude - that the whole tribe is struggling and if she contributed more, she'd feel better.
Comfort her and ask her how she's feeling.
Invite her to go hunting with you to get her spirits up.
Scold her and tell her to improve her attitude - that the whole tribe is struggling and if she contributed more, she'd feel better.
Comfort them and ask them how they're feeling.
Scold them and tell them to improve their attitudes - that the whole tribe is struggling and if they contributed more, they'd feel better.
Keep them both occupied. Have Syla help with smoking meat and have Jeneth help washing furs.
Invite Syla to go hunting with you to get her spirits up and have Jeneth cook the meat upon returning.
Greet them. Ask them about the area and if they have any information while motioning to your men to ready their weapons in case things escalate.
Draw your weapons and order your men to attack.
Agree with your father. Focus on gathering as much food as possible.
Agree with your brother. Focus on erecting defenses and assigning patrols to ensure the safety of your village.
Tell her how much you appreciate her hard work and all that she's been doing for you lately, including cooking meals and supporting you with your responsibilities.
Organize some of the masons to build a larger hut for the both of you to make room for the coming child.
Lecture her on how she needs to compose herself better now that she will be mother of your child.
Tell her how much you appreciate her hard work and all that she's been doing for you lately, including cooking meals and supporting you with your responsibilities.
Organize a tribal ritual for her with the shaman and medicine man to help honor her for bearing your child, but also reinforce your expectations.
Lecture her on how she needs to compose herself better now that she will be mother of your child.
Tell them both how much you appreciate them and all they've been doing to support you and the tribe.
Lecture them on how they need to compose themselves better and let them know what you will expect of them now that they will be the mothers of your children.
Organize a tribal ritual to honor your wives for their pregnancies.
Ignore them. They're grown women and they can resolve their issues on their own.
Tell them they can get into the village by crossing the stream to the south. There are less guards posted there and they wouldn't expect them.
Tell them nothing.
Tell them what they want.
Tell them nothing.
Try to find your wife and save her from her fate.
Try to find your father or brother if they're still alive so you can plot an escape.
Try to find your father and brother so you can organize a revolt.
Wait for One-Eye and use Jeneth as a distraction to assassinate him.
Try to find Jeneth.
Try to find Syla.

Pull out your bow and start firing on the raiders. You're uphill and you have the advantage of high ground, but the raiders are awfully close to the foragers. If your aim isn't true, you could hit one of your people instead.
Pull out your bow, but stand up and yell at the raiders, announcing your presence, and warn them to run.
Sneak up on them in the dim light and charge them in close-quarters combat.
Tell them to free your people or you will shoot them.
Bluff. Tell them you have reinforcements coming and they should run before they come.
Tell them your tribe is very powerful and crossing you could result in severe consequences later.
Join your brother in his assault.
Let your brother go alone. It's too risky and you're needed at the village.
Join your brother in the frontal assault. Putting all your eggs in one basket will be risky, but it could end the battle quickly.
Lead a secondary group to attack the raiders' flank while they are distracted with your brother's primary assault.
Convene on your brother's position to support him directly. Riskier, but could end the battle quicker.
Attack camps from the rear and start burning all the tents and supplies to spread confusion.
Kill her. She has dishonored you and if you let her live, no one in the tribe will ever respect you again.
Banish her from the tribe.
Stand with your father and fight back.
Gather the women and children and escape.
Stand with your father and fight back.
Gather the women and children and escape.
Stand with your father and fight back.
Gather the women and children and escape.
Stand with your father and fight back.
Gather the women and children and escape.
Stand with your father and fight back.
Gather the women and children and escape.
Stand with your father and fight back.
Gather the women and children and escape.
Forgive them. There's no sense in leaving behind more wounds before passing.
Spite them. You are paying the ultimate price for their selfishness and they should pay a price too.
Talk to her. She is quite lovely and your age. Your father will marry you off to someone eventually - probably a match of convenience. You may as well try and connect with someone you like.

Keep to yourself. She is too lovely for you. She would never be interested in a cripple like you, and if she were to reject your company, word would quickly spread around the tribe and no other girl would want anything to do with you either.
Reassure her. You just want to talk.
Impress her. Mention how you saved your father's life.
Threaten her. You are a powerful young man and crossing you would result in much worse consequences than any damage to her reputation.
Assert yourself. Tell her you understand what it means for her reputation to be associated with you, but that you don't live in fear of other people's opinions and neither should she.
Apologize to the others for being such a burden and hope they will have some sympathy for you.
Disappear into the wilderness. No one will miss you and it will improve your tribe's chances for survival.
Try to survive in the caves your tribe used as shelter in seasons past.
Camp out in the forest.
Tell her you're sorry for being so aggressive, but it's the only way you would be able to get through to her.
Tell her she needs to respect you more or there will be consequences later.
Spend the time talking with some of the elders learning as much as you can about managing the tribe.
Keep to yourself and avoid bothering anyone any more than you already have.
Flirt with her. She clearly likes you and will surely welcome your advances... probably.
Play it safe. You like her, but you don't want to push your luck and drive her away.
Try to make yourself useful by asking the elders how you can help.
Keep to yourself and be glad that you haven't been noticed.
Get closer and hide behind the bushes to hear what they're talking about.
Limp your way back to the village to warn your father and the elders of the intruders.
Scream out and get their attention. Bluff that armed men from your tribe are almost here.
Keep quiet. There's nothing you can do and you must stay alive to inform your father of what happened.

Accept your father's judgment. You are undeserving of anyone better and causing disagreement right now while the tribe is struggling could be disastrous. Besides, if you insisted on choosing your own bride and none others accepted, you would become the laughing stock of the entire tribe (more so than you've already been). Perhaps you would not be able to marry ever again at all.
Insist that you choose your own bride instead.
Attempt to take control of the situation.
Abandon the village, your wife, and the others, and run for the hills.
Tell them to hide in their homes and you'll negotiate with the raiders when they come.
Tell them they should come with you, abandon the village, and run for the hills. Let the raiders loot whatever they want.
Give them whatever they want so long as they leave your tribe alone.
Refuse. Tell them if they don't leave, you'll order your men to attack.
Ask Dara to marry you.
Back down. Tell your father you changed your mind and you'll accept Helga after all.
Order the villagers to take shelter, rally and arm the men, and prepare to have an audience with the raiders.
Abandon the village and hide in the hills. The raiders will loot the village, but your concern is for the safety of your people.
Make it seem like you and a few unarmed elders are there to negotiate, then when the raiders have their guard down, have your armed men come out of hiding in the huts and tents and ambush them.
Give them whatever they want so long as they leave your tribe alone.
Refuse. Tell them if they don't leave, you'll order your men to attack.

Agree with your brother. The raiders are ruthless and they're assuredly defiling the women right now. Any time wasted puts their lives in more and more danger and you must do anything possible to save Dara.
Agree with your father. Send a party to negotiate and trade for the women's release. It's the best chance you have to keep the women alive.
Accept your role. Somebody needs to be able to warn the tribe in case of defeat. You're crippled and you'll be nothing but a liability in battle.
Insist that you join them.  They will need every man and you can use a bow to provide support.
Return to the village and warn them of the defeat. They must be warned to leave the steppes before the raiders come searching for vengeance.
Take your bow and arrows and get closer to the raider camp to get a better assessment of the situation.

Get into position near the tent, throw a stone to distract the two guards, then quickly shoot them with your bow. Once you free your brother and your captured tribesmen, you can regroup and figure out what to do.

Steal some raider clothing off one of the corpses and impersonate a raider. Raise a false alarm of reinforcements of your people coming from the north. Then, once the guards leave their posts, free your brother and his men.

Leave and follow your dead father's instructions. Return to warn your tribe so they can escape the raiders' vengeance. You are a cripple and there's nothing more than you can do. Playing a hero and dying or getting captured now will mean your people will receive no warning. You are playing with their lives.
Try to get into position where you can get a clean look at One-Eye, then assassinate him with your bow.
Try to find the tent where the women are being kept and sneak away with them in the chaos.
Accept your role. Somebody needs to be able to warn the tribe in case of defeat. You're crippled and you'll be nothing but a liability in battle.
Insist that you join them.  They will need every man and you can use a bow to provide support.
Insist on leading a hunting party with a few of the remaining young men to shore up the food stores.
Take one of the dogs south to try and track your brother's hunting party.
Stay out of it and let the tribal elders decide. They know best.
Offer to scavenge for berries.
Offer to hunt some of the cave rats.
Back down.
Your father had taught you how to trap before he died. Offer to set some traps in the nearby woods.
You had accompanied some of the fishers when you were younger. Offer to try to spearfish.
Plead to be allowed to track your brother. If they can give you some time, you know you can find him.
Let the elders sort out the situation. Putting yourself on the line will accomplish nothing, and your brother is probably already dead.
Take command of the tribe. Your father was leader by blood, and with your brother missing, you have a fair claim to leadership.
Take a dog and search for your brother yourself.
Abandon the tribe. They will never respect you. The tribe is falling apart and you're better off on your own.
Take one of the dogs and go find your brother alone. If you don't do something, no one will.
Back down. You're not capable of surviving alone - it would be suicide, and this is not what you signed up for.
Cut through the Bonewoods. Time is of the essence if you hope for the dog to pick up the scent of the hunting party.
Skirt around the woods through the southern wastes. The woods are too dangerous to travel alone - doing so would be a serious risk.
Make camp and begin again at dawn. You've been traveling all day and you need the rest, and it's too dangerous to travel in the dark.
Light a torch and keep going. Your brother could be in danger and with your father gone, the survival of the tribe could depend on him since there are no other leaders to replace him.
Keep going into the southern wastes. In your heart, you know your brother is out there somewhere.
Turn back and return to the village. This has been a fool's errand and you should leave now while you still have your life and report to your tribesmen that your brother is nowhere to be found.
Throw some food to distract the wolves and run.
Roar ferociously and wave your torch to scare them away.
Pull out your stone hatchet and fight them.
Hide out in the nearby cave.
Throw the torch at them and run into the darkness.
Attempt to crawl out of the ravine.
Call out for help.
Grit your teeth and pull yourself out of the ravine through sheer will.
Crawl back to the village.
Set the injury with clay and camp out until it heals.
Return to the village. This was way more than you bargained for and it's time to head home. You've done the best you can.
Continue pursuing your brother. You haven't come all this way for nothing.
Cover their wounds and help them back to the village. He's your brother and you'll do whatever it takes to save him.
Leave them for dead. Your brother never cared for you and risking your life for him now would be foolish. Take his amulet as proof of his death and return to the village.
Bind their wounds, build a sled, and drag them home.
Set up camp. You're unlikely to find a better place and with the fresh water and nearby berries you can rest and stock up for the journey ahead.
Keep going. There's still some light out and you're already taking the long way around - you have no time to spare if your brother is in danger.
Keep going. You have to find your brother.
Return home and notify the tribe your brother is nowhere to be found. You did your best.
Follow the tracks. If your brother is still alive, you're the only hope he and the tribe has.
Turn back. Your brother is probably dead and you must return to the tribe. Putting yourself at risk now will do no one any good.
Return home. There's a good chance your brother and any others are dead and walking into the camp alone would be suicide.
Attempt to infiltrate the camp and find your brother. If there's a chance your brother or any of the hunters are alive, you have to take it.
Look in the large tent on the edge of the camp. It's worn and dingy and the least habitable of the structures there.
Look in the pen where the animals are kept. It's large enough to hold prisoners as well.
Ambush one of the guards and get him to tell you where the prisoners are held.
Yes. You've come this far...
No. You've already risked too much. You've done the best you could. It's time to retreat and head back to the village.
Tie him up and gag him.  He might get away or make a racket and draw attention, even while restrained.
Kill him. Dead men don't make noise, but they bleed a lot.
Surrender and ask for mercy. Explain your quest to find your brother and that you mean no harm encroaching upon their territory.
Run. The Witch Lords are known for their ruthlessness and cruelty. But if caught, you will surely be punished.
Gamble. Tell them you are a representative of your tribe and you are here on a diplomatic mission to establish relations with the Witch Lords.
Greet them as friends. Smile and tell them you are happy to see them and are in need of assistance.
Try and grab one of the stones to use it to cut your ropes later.
Do nothing. If they catch you, they will surely kill you.
Offer your dog, your tools, food, supplies, and everything you've brought with you on your journey.
Tell them you have stores of food, water, and clothing back at your village.
Reassure them that you mean no harm and are simply in search of your missing people.
Tell them you are in search of your missing brother and his hunting party, and your tribe has offered a bounty for any information regarding their whereabouts.
Try and comfort her.
Let her be. Being around you could damage her reputation.
Try to get through to her.
Scold her for treating you so poorly.
Tell her you understand how worried she must be as you are concerned for your brother as well.
Try to convince her that your brother would not want her to remain in danger on his behalf and that you can come back once the storm has passed.
Give in to her demands. It is apparent she will not budge and it would be best to shore up where you are and prepare for the storm.
Go to investigate.
Go back to bed.
Stay put and wait out the storm.
Urge Liana and her family to seek shelter in the caves nearby. They sometimes flood in heavy storms, but if you remain in the village, you will surely be overwhelmed.
Argue that you have a rightful claim to leadership as your father's last son remaining with the tribe.
Criticize them for being so combative and unable to come up with any solutions.
Back down. The elders are clearly aggravated and it's not worth getting into trouble.
Tell them they have no choice. They are incompetent and without decisive action, the tribe will fall apart.
Ridicule them for being so gutless and selfish and tell them your father would be disgusted with them were he alive.
Wait for your brother. Remain in place and figure out a strategy to find him. He's out there somewhere and you can't give up on him now.
Begin the migration. Accept the reality that your brother is probably dead and you have to do what's best for the tribe.
The Yagaro brothers (hunters). They are excellent archers and trackers, but inconsistent and not known for their brute strength.
Jayroc and Noa (masons). They are stone cutters used to heavy hitting and manual labor. They're extremely tough and resilient, but reckless and untrained in hunting and tracking.
Focus on stocking up on food. Send out every able body to hunt and gather.
Focus on fortifying the village. Cut trees to divert potential flood paths and reinforce the tents and huts.
Fortify the village. Send the tribesmen out in the storm to do their best to reinforce the housing. You have to wait for your scouting party to return.

Begin the migration. The storm is abating very little and it seems that it's only going to get worse in the coming days. However, migrating now in the heart of storm season will be extremely perilous.
Stay put. It's too dangerous to take action now that the storm is upon you.
Send out a hunting and gathering party. You have few able bodies to send, but it's either that or starve.

Begin the migration. The storm is abating very little and it seems that it's only going to get worse in the coming days. However, migrating now in the heart of storm season will be extremely perilous.
Stay put. It's too dangerous to take action now that the storm is upon you.
Join the hunters and aid in procuring food for the migration.
Spend time with the elders learning more about management of the tribe.
Advise him to take the eastern plains road. Your people have suffered so much already and it's necessary to find them a new home as quickly as possible.
Advise him to take the valley road. The road less travelled will offer greater refuge.
Accost them. Ask them where they're headed and if they have any news on events in the area.
Ignore them. Avoid interacting with them and prepare your weapons in case they get any ideas.
Agree with your brother and retreat. You are unprepared to fight open battle after such a long and weary journey. There's too much at stake.
Organize your men into groups, hide the women and children, and prepare for battle. They are mounted and they will outrun you as you retreat anyhow.
Agree with your brother. Negotiate terms for a truce and give them some food to appease them.
Disagree with your brother. You cannot give in to the raiders' demands. They will never be satisfied and they are clearly intimidated by your organized warriors. Now is the time to make a stand.
Greet them and ask what you can do for them.
Pull out weapons and attack. The horsemen outnumber you and seem better trained and better armed. Fighting them would probably result in your people being slaughtered.
Agree with your brother. You cannot let the raiders have your women. Prepare for battle.
Disagree with your brother. The raiders are armed and mounted and would slaughter your people here and now. Better to try negotiating with them and make compromises.
Take him with you. He will be a burden, but he will be unable to survive on his own.
Leave him be. You've helped him as much as you could and you cannot burden your tribe.
Lead the hunters on a short hunting expedition. The valley area is not rich with fauna, but the tribe could really use some meat.
Lead some foragers to try and gather some roots, berries, and other edibles to tide you over.
Move quickly. Catch as many fish as you can and leave before you encounter trouble.
Move cautiously. Post guards to watch for bears and be as quiet and low profile as possible.
Prepare for negotiation.
Prepare for war.
Explain how you are currently struggling with a food shortage and you promise to deliver more food later.
Beg for forgiveness and lenience.
Prepare defensive positions and have your archers attack as soon as the horsemen come within range.
Prepare an ambush. Have your men hide and feign negotiation, then once the enemies' guard is down, strike.
Develop a war strategy to crush the raiders once and for all.
Develop a negotiation strategy to create lasting peace.
Offer a division of territory, clearly demarcating boundaries and promise not to trespass on the raiders' hunting grounds.
Offer a lifetime of your servitude in exchange for peace.
Attack the raiders at their camp late at night.
Lay a trap for the raiders. Lure them with promises of food and women, then attack.
Urge him to round up the men and make an attack on the raider's camp to try and retrieve the women.
Go to the raider's camp yourself and try to negotiate the women's release.
Charge into camp and make a head on attack.
Wait till night and infiltrate their camp.
Help your brother.
Save the women.
Take only a few men and try to find the women, free them, and sneak out.
Bring your full group of men and kill all raiders you come across.
Offer to pay regular tribute of food and supplies.
Offer your own personal lifetime servitude.
Go north to the mountains and seek out the Northern Caves.
Go south to the wetlands in search of the Isle of Skorne.
Take the northern mountain road. It's the fastest path to your destination, but it's also used by the clans of the Mountain People who are known to be violent and erratic.
Take the long way around through the Bonewoods. You can avoid the Mountain Clans, but it will be a tougher journey and the greater risk for encountering predators.
Attack them.
Try to talk your way out of it.
Negotiate a temporary truce.
Attempt a negotiation, get their guard down, then when they least suspect it, kill their leader.
Attack them.
Turn back and take the Bonewoods instead.
Ambush them.
Move quickly to get through the Bonewoods as fast as possible.
Take a slower, quiet pace to avoid drawing any attention from predators, but you will have to spend the night in the woods.
Fight the wolves. Get your men together and make an immediate attack.
Run and let the surrounded tribe members die. The wolves are large and imposing and it wouldn't be worth risking your life or the lives of the others for but a few stragglers.
Throw them some food and hope that appeases them.
Sit tight and hope they go away.
Light fires and try to scare them away.
Build rafts and take the river. The river is flooded after the storm and moving very quickly. You will reach your destination faster, but the fury of the rapids is treacherous.
Take the long way around through the marshes. It will be less risky, but it will be a tough journey on foot as the marshes will be soaked from the storm.
Keep going. You're almost there.
Stop and finish the rest of the journey on foot.
Set up camp and spend the time digging out the carts.
Leave the carts and carry whatever supplies you can by hand.
Go after the scouts yourself.
Wait the night out and hope for the best in the morning.
Reach in and pull them out.
Leave them for dead. If you reach out, they'll pull you in and you'll die too.
Tear off a tree branch and have them grab it to pull them out.
Tell them to stop panicking, pull their legs to their chests, and slowly pull themselves out.
Try to find them on your own.
Leave the scouts behind and continue the journey.
Follow the river. It's likely to lead to the Isle of Skorne, but you don't know which fork to follow.
Follow the high trail. It leads deeper into the marshes, but where it leads, you're not sure.
Volunteer to find the blood moss yourself. You know the way and your brother is needed at the village.
Let your brother go instead. He is better suited to survive the journey and if you fail, it will cost your father his life.
Take the mountain path. You'll avoid the wetlands, but the path is treacherous and known for its pitfalls.
Take the river path. The terrain is more level, but the rivers are flooded at this time of year and paths will be muddy and unforgiving.
Turn back and take the river path instead. Your father will lose valuable time due to your indecision, but he'll never get the medicine he needs if you die on the rocks now.
Keep going. If you turn back now, your father will surely succumb to rot.
Try to cross the river. Your father is dying and there is no time to lose.
Try to find a way around. Time is of the essence, but you'll do your father no favors getting swept away in the rapids.
Try to slowly wade out.
Try to quickly swim out before you get stuck.
Try to pull yourself out. A tree branch is hanging nearby - you might be able to reach it.
You remember your father teaching you how to get out of quick sand. Pull your legs up and slowly crawl out.
Intervene. Your father would normally negotiate the problem, but he's unconscious. If you don't do something, no one will.
Stay out of it. You're just an adolescent and getting in the way could put you seriously at risk. The elders will handle the situation.
Accept responsibility as leader.
Let the tribe elders lead.
Agree with the masons. Head south to the warmer wetlands.
Agree with the hunters. Head north to the mountains to avoid the coming storm.
Set a slow pace. There are women and children and going slower would be less strain on your people, but you will use more food, and you will be at greater risk for being overtaken by the storm.
Set a quick pace. You might be able to outrun the storm, but it will be hard on your people.
Set up camp and wait out the storm. You are still several days from the wetlands.
Keep going. Staying put would mean getting stuck in the open.
Keep waiting. Moving now could put your people in even more danger.
Move on and seek shelter elsewhere. Staying put would be certain death.
Build some temporary makeshift shelters to wait out the storm.
Set up camp and lead a short hunting party to stock up.
Keep going. The storm is still on its way and there's no time to waste.
Camp out and let the elders rest, but risk getting caught up in the storm.
Keep going, but at a slower pace.
Leave those who can't keep up behind.  Though many won't like it, you must do what's best for the tribe.
Take the north mountain road. It has easier accessibility and allows for faster travel, but it's also used by clans of the Mountain People who are erratic and fearsome.
Go through the Bonewoods. Travel will be harder and you'll be more exposed to predators, but the trees will provide cover.

Go at a slow pace to avoid attention and send scouts out ahead. They will let you know if they encounter any of the Mountain Clans. However, you are still in the path of the storm and it is quite near.
Go at a fast pace. It might draw more attention, but you need to do all you can to avoid the storm.
Find a place to hide and wait out the storm. Your people are weary and would not withstand battle with the Mountain Clans.
Round up the men and prepare to charge the ranks of the Mountain People in your way. The storm will destroy you if you don't.
Lay an ambush for the Mountain People, then slaughter them once they fall into your trap.
Keep moving and hope you can find some place better to wait out the storm.
Stay put and hope for the best.
Build some makeshift shelters with stone to brace yourselves against the wind and try to start some fires for warmth.
Spare them and take them as prisoners. They will be extra mouths to feed and more trouble, but you cannot execute them in cold blood and set such a ruthless example for your own tribe.
Kill them. It's not worth the risk bringing them along.
Let them go. You don't want to execute them and you don't want the burden of bringing them along, but they will assuredly inform their clans of your presence and location.
Set guards and camp out the night, then resume traveling in the morning.
Light torches and keep going to get through the Bonewoods as quickly as possible. The woods are known to be extremely dangerous and camping out could be a serious risk.
Set up a defensive perimeter with planted torches and wooden stakes to ward off any predators.
Go with the masons. Head south to warmer wetlands.
Go with the hunters. Head north to the mountains.
Go on your own.
Camp out with the hunters and wait out the storm. However, there will assuredly be more bad weather down the line going in this direction towards the wetlands.
Abandon the masons. They don't know what they're doing and you'll be better off on your own.
Stick with the hunters in hopes that they'll sort their disagreements out. You won't be able to survive in the wilderness alone.
Abandon the hunters. They don't know what they're doing and you'll be better off on your own.
Stick with the masons. You've traveled too far and you've no other options.
Leave and go on your own.
Try to survive on your own at the old caves the tribe used the past winter.
Try to find acceptance with the Mountain People - They are fearsome and unpredictable, but strong and able to survive the harshness of the unforgiving wilds.
Scavenge for berries.
Hunt some of the cave rats.
Set some traps in the nearby woods.
Try to spearfish.
Greet them.
Hide.
Attack them before they realize you're there.
Offer them some of your food - You can't see your people suffer.
Turn them away - They betrayed you and you should give them what they deserve: nothing.
Stay put in the caves and weather out the storm. The caves might shield you from the elements, but they are also known to flood in bad storms.
Try to take shelter near the mountains.
Stay put in the caves and weather out the storm. The caves might shield you from the elements, but they are also known to flood in bad storms.
Try to find acceptance with the Mountain People. They are harsh and unpredictable, but far better equipped to survive.
Stay put in the caves and weather out the storm. It will provide you some shelter, but the caves are known to flood, which would be especially difficult with the others.
Head out north towards the mountains. You might be able to avoid the storm, but you'll have to camp out in the open and expose yourselves to the elements.
Lead them on a migration. They are your people and though they have mistreated you in the past, this seems like an opportunity to build a new future for yourself and for them.
Leave them to their fate. Return to the wilderness and live on your own.
Lead your people.
Go on your own.
Take the high pass - It's a shorter path to the village, but at a higher altitude and more dangerous.
Take the low path - It's a longer way around, but safer. However, the longer journey will mean greater risk of running out of supplies and energy.
Beg for mercy - Explain how you were abandoned by your tribe.
Offer your service  Promise to perform whatever labors they want in exchange for food and shelter.
Bend over and do what you're told - There's no telling what they will do if you refuse.
Refuse - You won't let them take your dignity.
Pick berries and return promptly - Maybe if you are obedient, they will show mercy.
Try to sneak away - It was a grave mistake coming here and you need to leave before they do anything worse to you.
Go with them - Maybe with your continued compliance they will become merciful.
Try to escape - By now it's clear that with them you are doomed to the life of a slave. You'd rather die trying to escape and live a better life.
Try to survive on your own in the mountain caves.
Try to make it down the mountainside to the forest.
Take a drink - You are desperate and have no choice.
Move on - The water looks unclean and you could get sick, making matters worse.
Focus on building a base of operations. You will need a strong foothold in the region in order to provide shelter and survive the challenges ahead.
Focus on exploring the island and finding food sources and herbal remedies to ensure the health of your tribe.
Kill them. They are a threat to your tribe and this will be an opportune way to stock up on some meat as well.
Leave them be. It's not worth the risk attacking them.
Attempt to befriend them. Give them some food and show them you mean no harm. It could be risky as the dogs might be hostile.
Choose Yolena - A daughter of the hunters. She is thin, elegant, and supportive. You will gain further support from her family and have greater access to food.
Choose Evon - A daughter of the masons. She is full-figured, comely, and warm. Her family will be pleased and you'll gain further support to your shelters.
Lead a hunting and foraging expedition to gather whatever food you can. The rain is unceasing and the risks are high.
Wait for the storms to abate. The storms will not last forever and it's too dangerous to go out when the winds are so violent.
Have the masons build makeshift shelters and reinforce the buildings.
Leave for the caves uphill on the island. The village is a wreck and you can bide time in the caves till the storm passes.
Scream and beg for mercy.
Tell them you're the tribe's leader and offer to take the cannibals to your village. Promise them many more people in exchange for your life.
Keep quiet and bide your time.
Cut away the rope binding you with a nearby stone and make a break for it.
Stumble away in the night. You are bound, but not caged, and you have enough freedom to lurch away. But you might catch attention.
Wait until a better opportunity in the morning. It's too risky to go now. But a better opportunity might not come.
Prepare for the attack. Lay an ambush for the cannibals. Bait them into coming into your camp and then assault them when they least expect it.
Retreat from the island and return to your tribe's previous home.

Have some of your strongest men camp by a fire very visibly while hiding their weapons. Meanwhile, you and the rest of the men, will hide amongst the huts of the villages and wait to spring your trap.
Leave the village deserted and camp out in the forest of the island. Have your men climb the trees and lure the cannibals into range to shoot them with arrows.
Attempt to attack them.
Offer yourself in return for your wife and others. Tell them you are leader of the tribe and your blood will nourish them with special power.
Run with the others and leave the captured tribesmen to their fates.
Focus on stocking up food stores. Food is hard to come by on the mountains and you will need all you can get as quickly as possible.
Focus on logistics. Send out scouting parties to understand the terrain, find better sources of food, gather firewood, and fortify the caves to protect from the cold.
Instruct your people to avoid the village of the Mountain People as much as possible.
Send sentries to keep an eye on the village and make note of any developments.
Go with some of your advisors on an ambassadorial trip to the village and see if you can negotiate a truce. It could be risky.
Lead a preemptive assault on the village before winter comes to ensure no competition for resources.
Offer food and supplies as tribute in return for peace. The cost could be high.
Ask for mutually beneficial peace and imply catastrophic war if they don't agree. Higher risk, higher reward.
Wait till night and infiltrate their village under the cover of darkness.
Make a full frontal assault right now and overwhelm them with shock and awe.
Start lighting fires and smoke the Mountain People out.
Go house to house and kill them in their sleep.
Take the lead and finish them off while you still have the element of surprise.
Take a defensive position and draw the enemy out. This might reduce your own casualties, but you'd also be giving the enemy a chance to regroup.

Spare them and take them as prisoners. Showing mercy would be good for the consciences of your people, and in addition, they could be useful with their knowledge of the local lands. However, the extra mouths to feed could be a strain on your tribe, especially with the coming winter months.
Kill them and loot their supplies. They're not worth the trouble.
Choose Yolena -  A daughter of the hunters. She is thin, elegant, and supportive. You will gain further support from her family and have greater access to food.
Choose Evon - A daughter of the masons. She is full-figured, comely, and warm. Her family will be pleased and you'll gain further support to your shelters.

Choose Gorgana - A daughter of the Mountain People. She is tough and brutal, accustomed to the hard winters on the mountain, but she has a savage beauty to her that draws all sorts of. Choose her and you can benefit from her experience and gain support from her people, integrating them into your tribe completely, but it will surely sow discontent amongst the people of your own.
Lead a hunting and foraging expedition to gather whatever food you can. The bitter cold is brutal and the risks are high.
Enforce a strict rationing policy. The winter will not last forever and as soon as the weather abates, you will search for food then.
Lead an emergency hunting and foraging expedition. You are weak with hunger, the blizzard is brutal, and going out now could be suicide.
Wait it out until the blizzard abates. Though by the looks of it, the storm won't be stopping any time soon, and with the food stores so depleted, waiting could mean death.
Wait until some of the elders die and eat them.
Wait it out until the blizzard abates. But there's no guarantee that it will.
Wait until some of the elders die and eat them. Desperate times call for desperate measures.
Force her to eat. She must for the sake of the child.
Let her be. You won't force her if she refuses.
Try to survive as long as you can on your own.
Give up and die.
Have the masons go out into the blizzard and gather more materials to build barriers and fuel fires to combat the cold and the elements.
Huddle together for warmth and wait until the blizzard subsides to go out. It's too dangerous to go out now and you have enough food to survive for a while.
Go after them yourself. It could be dangerous, but if the masons have gotten into trouble, they may need help. The survival of your tribe could depend on it.
Sit tight and wait for them to come back. It's not worth the risk playing hero and they're perfectly capable of surviving on their own.
Prepare for battle. Arm your best men, set up barriers, get the women and children deeper in the caves, and make ready for a last stand.
Migrate. Gather up the supplies and head down the mountains taking shelter below the tree line. Winter is almost over and you don't want to risk any casualties.
Retreat. There are too many and it's best to return to the caves.
Head down anyway. You might be able to evade their notice.
Go on your own to distract them and lead them away while your people escape.
Grab your stone hatchet and attack them. You must kill these two and return to the caves to warn your people of the assault.
Offer your tribe's food in exchange for your lives and beg for mercy.
Prepare for battle. Arm your best men, set up barriers, get the women and children deeper in the caves, and make ready for a last stand.
Migrate. Gather up the supplies and head down the mountains taking shelter below the tree line. Winter is almost over and you don't want to risk any casualties.
